{{Infobox Athletics Championships |Name = II GANEFO |Logo = |Size = |Colour = |Optional caption = |Host city = [[Phnom Penh]], Cambodia |Dates = November and December 1966 |Stadium = |Nations participating = |Athletes participating = |Events = 31 |Previous = [[Athletics at the 1963 GANEFO|1963 Jakarta]] |Games = [[1966 GANEFO]] }}
At the '''[[1966 GANEFO]]''', the '''[[Athletics (sport)|athletics]]''' events were held in [[Phnom Penh]], Cambodia in November and December.<ref name=DB>Bell, Daniel (2003). ''Encyclopedia of International Games''. McFarland and Company, Inc. Publishers, Jefferson, North Carolina. {{ISBN|0-7864-1026-4}}.</ref> A total of 21 men's and 12 women's [[athletics events]] were contested at the competition.<ref name=GBR>[http://www.gbrathletics.com/ic/gang.htm GANEFO Games]. GBR Athletics. Retrieved on 2015-01-14.</ref> The program was the same as the previous edition, except that the men's [[decathlon]] and [[steeplechase (athletics)|steeplechase]] events were dropped. Composed entirely of athletes from Asian nations, the events served as a counterpart to the [[athletics at the 1966 Asian Games]], which featured largely Western-allied Asian nations.<ref>[http://www.gbrathletics.com/ic/asg.htm Asian Games]. GBR Athletics. Retrieved on 2015-01-14.</ref>
Continuing on from the [[Athletics at the 1963 GANEFO|first GANEFO]], China dominated the athletics competition, winning nineteen of the gold medals on offer. [[North Korea]] was the next most successful with ten gold medals. [[North Vietnam]], [[Syria]] and [[Cambodia]] each won one gold medal each.<ref name=GBR/>
[[Ni Zhiqin]], China's leading men's [[high jump]]er, was the only man to defend his title from the 1963 games. [[Zheng Fengrong]], a former world record holder, added the high jump gold to the defence of her [[women's pentathlon]] title and also a [[80 metres hurdles]] bronze. The most successful athlete of the tournament was [[Sin Kim-dan]], who won the [[200 metres]], [[400 metres]] and [[800 metres]] titles – this meant she managed to defend all her 1963 titles.<ref name=GBR/>
