[[File:Bernat Fenollar.jpeg|150px|thumbnail|right|Bernat Fenollar]] '''Bernat Fenollar''', also '''Mossèn (Bernat de) Fenollar''' ([[Valencian Community]], 1438 – [[Valencia, Spain|Valencia]], 28 February 1516) was a poet, cleric and chess player from Valencia, [[Spain]].<ref name=GEC>{{cite web |title=Bernat Fenollar |publisher=Gran Enciclopèdia Catalana |website=www.enciclopedia.cat |language=ca |url=http://www.enciclopedia.cat/EC-GEC-0026426.xml |accessdate=2015-08-07}}</ref> He was an abbot (the title "Mossèn" was often given to clergymen), had a position both in [[Valencia Cathedral]] and the [[University of Valencia]] as a professor of mathematics.<ref>[[Ricardo Calvo]], [https://sites.google.com/site/caroluschess/modern-history/the-origin-of-modern-chess/valencia-spain-the-cradle-of-european-chess Valencia Spain: The Cradle of European Chess], Presentation to the CCI (Chess Collectors International) May, 1998, [[Vienna]], [[Austria]].</ref>
He is one of the authors of ''[[Scachs d'amor]]'' or ''Chess of Love'', a poem based on a [[chess game]] between [[Francesc de Castellví]] and [[Narcís Vinyoles]],<ref>[http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1259987 Francesco di Castellvi vs Narciso Vinyoles], [[Valencia]], [[Spain]], 1475, [[Chessgames.com]].</ref> while Bernat Fenollar comments and establishes the rules.<ref name=GEC /><ref name=SdA>{{cite web |last=Sobrer |first=Josep Miquel |title=The English translation of Scachs d'Amor |publisher=Scachs d'Amor Org |website=www.scachsdamor.org |url=http://www.scachsdamor.org/ |accessdate=2015-08-07}}</ref> It is the first documented game played with the modern [[rules of chess]], at least concerning the moves of the [[queen (chess)|queen]] and [[bishop (chess)|bishop]].<ref name=SdA />
